module.exports = [
  [177, "The Evolution of Western Painting", "艺术", 2, "Western painting has undergone a remarkable evolution over the centuries, reflecting changing aesthetic values, technical innovations, and cultural shifts. From the realistic depictions of the Renaissance to the abstract expressions of the twentieth century, each movement has built upon and reacted against its predecessors.\n\nThe Renaissance introduced techniques including linear perspective and chiaroscuro that created unprecedented realism. Leonardo da Vinci's Mona Lisa exemplifies the period's mastery of light, shadow, and psychological depth. The Baroque period that followed emphasized drama, movement, and emotional intensity, as seen in Caravaggio's dramatic use of light.\n\nThe nineteenth century brought revolutionary changes. Impressionism, led by Claude Monet, rejected the academic tradition of precise detail in favor of capturing fleeting effects of light and color. Post-Impressionists including Van Gogh and Cezanne pushed further, using color and form to express emotion and structure rather than visual appearance. These movements paved the way for the radical departures of the twentieth century.\n\nModern art saw the emergence of abstraction, cubism, surrealism, and expressionism. Picasso's cubism fragmented reality into multiple viewpoints. Kandinsky created the first purely abstract paintings. The abstract expressionists, including Jackson Pollock, made the act of painting itself the subject of art. Today, contemporary painting embraces pluralism, with artists freely drawing from multiple traditions. The evolution of painting demonstrates that art is not merely about representing reality but about exploring new ways of seeing and experiencing the world.",
  "西方绘画在几个世纪中经历了显著的演变，反映了不断变化的审美价值观、技术创新和文化转变。从文艺复兴的现实描绘到二十世纪的抽象表现，每个运动都建立在前辈的基础上并对其做出反应。\n\n文艺复兴引入了线性透视和明暗对比等技术，创造了前所未有的现实主义。达芬奇的蒙娜丽莎体现了该时期对光影和心理深度的精通。\n\n十九世纪带来了革命性的变化。由莫奈领导的印象主义拒绝了精确细节的学院传统，转而捕捉光影的瞬间效果。后印象派包括梵高和塞尚进一步推进，使用色彩和形式来表达情感和结构。\n\n现代艺术见证了抽象、立体主义、超现实主义和表现主义的兴起。毕加索的立体主义将现实分解为多个视角。康定斯基创作了第一批纯抽象绘画。绘画的演变表明艺术不仅仅是再现现实，而是探索观看和体验世界的新方式。",
  328, [["What techniques did the Renaissance introduce?","Abstract expressionism","Linear perspective and chiaroscuro","Drip painting","Digital art","B","文章指出文艺复兴引入了线性透视和明暗对比等技术。"],["What did Impressionism seek to capture?","Precise anatomical detail","Fleeting effects of light and color","Political messages","Mathematical patterns","B","文章指出印象主义转而捕捉光影的瞬间效果。"],["Who created the first purely abstract paintings?","Leonardo da Vinci","Claude Monet","Kandinsky","Picasso","C","文章指出康定斯基创作了第一批纯抽象绘画。"],["What did Baroque painting emphasize?","Minimalism and simplicity","Drama, movement, and emotional intensity","Only religious themes","Only landscapes","B","文章指出巴洛克时期强调戏剧性、运动和情感强度。"]]],
  [178, "Music as Universal Language", "艺术", 1, "Music is often described as a universal language, capable of transcending cultural and linguistic barriers to evoke shared emotional experiences. Every known human society has developed musical traditions, suggesting that music satisfies a fundamental human need.\n\nThe universality of music extends across multiple dimensions. All cultures use structured sequences of sounds organized by rhythm, melody, and harmony. Certain musical features appear consistently across cultures: lullabies tend to be slow and soothing, while dance music tends to be fast and rhythmic. Research suggests that basic emotional responses to music, such as feeling uplifted by major keys and melancholic by minor keys, may be shared across cultures.\n\nMusic serves diverse functions in human societies. It accompanies rituals and ceremonies, from weddings to funerals. It facilitates social bonding, as anyone who has sung in a choir or danced at a concert can attest. It preserves cultural memory, transmitting stories and values across generations. It provides emotional expression, allowing people to process feelings that words alone cannot capture.\n\nThe neuroscience of music reveals why it affects us so deeply. Music activates reward systems in the brain, releasing dopamine and producing pleasure. It also engages areas involved in emotion, memory, and motor control simultaneously. Music therapy has been shown to help patients with neurological conditions including Parkinson's disease, stroke recovery, and Alzheimer's disease. The power of music to move us, both emotionally and physically, reflects its deep roots in human biology and culture.",
  "音乐常被描述为一种通用语言，能够超越文化和语言障碍唤起共享的情感体验。每个已知的人类社会都发展了音乐传统，表明音乐满足了基本的人类需求。\n\n音乐的普遍性延伸到多个维度。所有文化都使用由节奏、旋律和和声组织的结构化声音序列。某些音乐特征在各文化中一致出现：摇篮曲往往缓慢而舒缓，而舞蹈音乐往往快速而有节奏。\n\n音乐在人类社会中服务于多种功能。它伴随仪式和典礼，促进社会纽带，保存文化记忆，提供情感表达。\n\n音乐的神经科学揭示了它为何如此深刻地影响我们。音乐激活大脑中的奖赏系统，释放多巴胺并产生快感。音乐疗法已被证明可以帮助帕金森病、中风康复和阿尔茨海默病患者。音乐感动我们的力量反映了它在人类生物学和文化中的深层根源。",
  324, [["What basic emotional response to music may be shared across cultures?","Only sadness","Feeling uplifted by major keys and melancholic by minor keys","Only excitement","No emotional responses are shared","B","文章指出大调令人振奋和小调令人忧郁的基本情感反应可能跨文化共享。"],["What does music activate in the brain?","Only the auditory cortex","Reward systems, releasing dopamine and producing pleasure","Only the language areas","Only the visual areas","B","文章指出音乐激活大脑中的奖赏系统，释放多巴胺并产生快感。"],["What conditions has music therapy been shown to help with?","Only anxiety","Parkinson's disease, stroke recovery, and Alzheimer's disease","Only insomnia","Only physical injuries","B","文章指出音乐疗法已被证明可以帮助帕金森病、中风康复和阿尔茨海默病患者。"],["What do lullabies tend to be across cultures?","Fast and rhythmic","Slow and soothing","Loud and chaotic","Atonal and dissonant","B","文章指出摇篮曲往往缓慢而舒缓。"]]],
  [179, "The Art of Architecture", "艺术", 1, "Architecture stands at the intersection of art and function, creating spaces that shelter human activity while expressing cultural values and aesthetic ideals. Throughout history, architectural styles have reflected the technologies, materials, and philosophies of their times.\n\nAncient architecture demonstrated remarkable engineering achievements. The Egyptian pyramids, built with massive stone blocks, have endured for over four thousand years. Greek temples perfected proportions and introduced the classical orders that would influence Western architecture for millennia. Roman engineering produced aqueducts, amphitheaters, and the Pantheon's unreinforced concrete dome, still the world's largest after two thousand years.\n\nGothic architecture transformed medieval Europe with its soaring cathedrals featuring pointed arches, ribbed vaults, and flying buttresses. These innovations allowed buildings to reach unprecedented heights, filling interiors with light through enormous stained glass windows. The Gothic cathedral represented both technical achievement and spiritual aspiration.\n\nModern architecture emerged in the twentieth century with new materials and philosophies. Steel and glass enabled skyscrapers that transformed urban skylines. The Bauhaus school championed functional design where form follows function. Contemporary architecture embraces sustainability, with green buildings incorporating energy efficiency, natural ventilation, and renewable materials. Today's architects face the challenge of creating structures that are not only beautiful and functional but also environmentally responsible, shaping cities that will serve future generations.",
  "建筑位于艺术与功能的交汇处，创造庇护人类活动的空间，同时表达文化价值和审美理想。纵观历史，建筑风格反映了其时代的技术、材料和哲学。\n\n古代建筑展示了非凡的工程成就。埃及金字塔已矗立四千多年。希腊神庙完善了比例，引入了影响西方建筑数千年的古典柱式。罗马工程产生了万神殿的无钢筋混凝土穹顶，两千年后仍是世界上最大的。\n\n哥特式建筑以高耸的大教堂改变了中世纪欧洲，其特点是尖拱、肋拱和飞扶壁。这些创新使建筑达到了前所未有的高度。\n\n现代建筑在二十世纪以新材料和哲学出现。钢和玻璃使摩天大楼成为可能。包豪斯学派倡导功能设计。当代建筑拥抱可持续性。今天的建筑师面临的挑战是创造不仅美观实用而且环境负责的结构。",
  326, [["What is still the world's largest unreinforced concrete dome?","The Egyptian pyramid","The Greek Parthenon","The Roman Pantheon's dome","The Gothic Notre Dame","C","文章指出万神殿的无钢筋混凝土穹顶两千年后仍是世界上最大的。"],["What characterized Gothic architecture?","Flat roofs and minimal decoration","Pointed arches, ribbed vaults, and flying buttresses","Only round arches","Only concrete structures","B","文章指出哥特式建筑的特点是尖拱、肋拱和飞扶壁。"],["What did the Bauhaus school champion?","Ornate decoration","Functional design where form follows function","Only traditional styles","Only religious architecture","B","文章指出包豪斯学派倡导形式服从功能的功能设计。"],["What challenge do today's architects face?","Only making buildings taller","Creating structures that are beautiful, functional, and environmentally responsible","Only reducing costs","Only using traditional materials","B","文章指出今天的建筑师面临的挑战是创造美观实用且环境负责的结构。"]]],
  [180, "Film as an Art Form", "艺术", 1, "Cinema, born in the late nineteenth century, has evolved from a technological novelty into one of the most influential art forms of the modern era. Film combines visual imagery, narrative, music, and performance into a uniquely powerful medium that can entertain, educate, and inspire.\n\nThe language of film developed rapidly. Early pioneers including Georges Melies discovered that editing could create illusions and tell stories. D.W. Griffith pioneered narrative techniques including close-ups, cross-cutting, and flashback. Soviet filmmakers including Eisenstein developed montage theory, demonstrating that the juxtaposition of images could create meaning beyond what either image conveyed alone.\n\nThe addition of sound in the late 1920s and color in the 1930s expanded film's expressive possibilities. The Hollywood studio system produced genre films that defined popular cinema, while filmmakers in Europe, Japan, and elsewhere developed distinct national cinemas with unique aesthetic traditions. The French New Wave of the 1960s challenged conventional filmmaking with innovative techniques and personal expression.\n\nDigital technology has transformed filmmaking in the twenty-first century. Computer-generated imagery enables visual effects that were previously impossible. Digital cameras have democratized filmmaking, allowing anyone with a smartphone to create and share videos. Streaming platforms have changed how audiences consume films, while raising questions about the future of theatrical exhibition. Despite these changes, the fundamental appeal of cinema remains: its power to tell stories that move audiences and illuminate the human condition.",
  "电影诞生于十九世纪末，已从技术新奇事物演变为现代最具影响力的艺术形式之一。电影将视觉图像、叙事、音乐和表演结合成一种独特的强大媒介。\n\n电影语言发展迅速。早期先驱发现剪辑可以创造幻觉和讲述故事。格里菲斯开创了特写、交叉剪辑和闪回等叙事技巧。苏联电影制作人发展了蒙太奇理论。\n\n1920年代后期添加声音和1930年代添加色彩扩展了电影的表现可能性。好莱坞制片厂制度制作了定义流行电影的类型片。1960年代的法国新浪潮以创新技术挑战了传统电影制作。\n\n数字技术在二十一世纪改变了电影制作。计算机生成图像使以前不可能的视觉效果成为可能。数字相机使电影制作民主化。流媒体平台改变了观众消费电影的方式。尽管发生了这些变化，电影的基本吸引力仍然存在：讲述感动观众和照亮人类处境的故事的力量。",
  330, [["What did early filmmakers discover about editing?","That it was unnecessary","That editing could create illusions and tell stories","That films should never be edited","That editing only slowed films down","B","文章指出早期先驱发现剪辑可以创造幻觉和讲述故事。"],["What did Soviet filmmakers develop?","The Hollywood studio system","Montage theory demonstrating that juxtaposition of images creates meaning beyond individual images","Sound technology","Color film","B","文章指出苏联电影制作人发展了蒙太奇理论，展示图像并置可以创造超越单个图像的意义。"],["What did the French New Wave do in the 1960s?","Only made documentaries","Challenged conventional filmmaking with innovative techniques and personal expression","Created the first sound films","Only used computer effects","B","文章指出法国新浪潮以创新技术挑战了传统电影制作。"],["What has digital technology done to filmmaking?","Made it more expensive and exclusive","Democratized filmmaking, allowing anyone with a smartphone to create videos","Eliminated all professional filmmakers","Only changed the sound quality","B","文章指出数字相机使电影制作民主化，允许任何有智能手机的人创作视频。"]]],
  [181, "Dance as Cultural Expression", "艺术", 1, "Dance is one of humanity's oldest art forms, serving as a means of expression, communication, and cultural identity across all civilizations. From ritual ceremonies to theatrical performances, dance reflects the values, beliefs, and aesthetics of the societies that create it.\n\nTraditional and folk dances preserve cultural heritage. Indian classical dance forms including Bharatanatyam and Kathak tell stories from Hindu mythology through precise gestures and expressions. African dance traditions emphasize community participation and rhythm as connections to ancestral spirits. Flamenco expresses the passion and history of the Romani people in Spain. These traditional forms are living repositories of cultural knowledge.\n\nBallet emerged in the courts of Renaissance Italy and France, evolving into a highly codified art form emphasizing technique, grace, and storytelling. The development of pointe work in the nineteenth century gave ballerinas an ethereal quality. Modern dance, pioneered by Isadora Duncan and Martha Graham in the early twentieth century, rejected ballet's rigid conventions in favor of more natural movement and emotional authenticity.\n\nContemporary dance continues to evolve, incorporating elements from multiple traditions and exploring new possibilities. Hip-hop dance originated in African American and Latino communities as a form of cultural expression and social commentary. Dance therapy uses movement to promote emotional, cognitive, and physical integration. Whether performed on grand stages or in community spaces, dance remains a vital form of human expression that connects mind, body, and spirit.",
  "舞蹈是人类最古老的艺术形式之一，作为表达、交流和文化认同的手段贯穿所有文明。从仪式典礼到戏剧表演，舞蹈反映了创造它的社会的价值观、信仰和美学。\n\n传统和民间舞蹈保存了文化遗产。印度古典舞蹈形式包括婆罗多舞和卡塔克舞通过精确的手势和表情讲述印度神话故事。非洲舞蹈传统强调社区参与和节奏。弗拉门戈表达了西班牙罗姆人的热情和历史。\n\n芭蕾舞在文艺复兴时期的意大利和法国宫廷中出现，演变为强调技巧、优雅和叙事的高度程式化艺术形式。现代舞由伊莎多拉·邓肯和玛莎·格雷厄姆在二十世纪初开创，拒绝了芭蕾舞的僵化惯例。\n\n当代舞蹈继续发展，融合多种传统的元素并探索新的可能性。嘻哈舞源于非裔美国人和拉丁裔社区。舞蹈疗法利用运动促进情感、认知和身体整合。无论是在大舞台上还是在社区空间，舞蹈仍然是连接心灵、身体和精神的重要人类表达形式。",
  328, [["What do Indian classical dance forms tell stories about?","Modern politics","Hindu mythology through precise gestures and expressions","European history","Scientific discoveries","B","文章指出印度古典舞蹈通过精确的手势和表情讲述印度神话故事。"],["Who pioneered modern dance?","Mikhail Baryshnikov","Isadora Duncan and Martha Graham","Fred Astaire","Rudolf Nureyev","B","文章指出现代舞由伊莎多拉·邓肯和玛莎·格雷厄姆开创。"],["Where did hip-hop dance originate?","In European ballet schools","In African American and Latino communities","In Japanese theaters","In Indian temples","B","文章指出嘻哈舞源于非裔美国人和拉丁裔社区。"],["What does dance therapy use to promote integration?","Only verbal communication","Movement to promote emotional, cognitive, and physical integration","Only music","Only medication","B","文章指出舞蹈疗法利用运动促进情感、认知和身体整合。"]]],
  [182, "Sculpture Through the Ages", "艺术", 2, "Sculpture, the art of creating three-dimensional forms, has been a fundamental mode of artistic expression since prehistoric times. From the earliest carved figurines to contemporary installations, sculpture has continually evolved in materials, techniques, and conceptual approaches.\n\nAncient sculpture demonstrated remarkable skill. Egyptian sculptures served religious and funerary purposes, following strict conventions of pose and proportion. Greek sculpture achieved unprecedented naturalism, culminating in works like the Parthenon sculptures that captured the human form in idealized perfection. Roman sculpture combined Greek aesthetic ideals with realistic portraiture that recorded individual characteristics.\n\nThe Renaissance revitalized sculpture with works by Donatello, Michelangelo, and Bernini. Michelangelo's David, carved from a single block of marble, exemplifies the period's belief in the inherent beauty of the human form. Bernini's dynamic compositions brought sculpture to life with dramatic movement and emotional intensity. Rodin broke with academic tradition in the nineteenth century, creating works that emphasized personal expression over idealized form.\n\nTwentieth-century sculpture expanded dramatically in both materials and concepts. Brancusi pursued simplified, essential forms. Henry Moore created large-scale abstract works. Alexander Calder introduced kinetic sculpture that moves. Installation art transformed entire spaces into sculptural experiences. Contemporary sculpture increasingly incorporates found objects, digital fabrication, and interactive elements, blurring boundaries between sculpture and other art forms while continuing to explore fundamental questions about space, form, and meaning.",
  "雕塑是创造三维形式的艺术，自史前时代以来一直是艺术表达的基本模式。从最早的雕刻小雕像到当代装置，雕塑在材料、技术和概念方法上不断演变。\n\n古代雕塑展示了非凡的技巧。埃及雕塑服务于宗教和丧葬目的。希腊雕塑实现了前所未有的自然主义。罗马雕塑将希腊美学理想与写实肖像结合。\n\n文艺复兴时期以多纳泰罗、米开朗基罗和贝尼尼的作品振兴了雕塑。米开朗基罗的大卫像体现了该时期对人体形式内在美的信念。贝尼尼的动态构图以戏剧性运动和情感强度赋予雕塑生命。\n\n二十世纪的雕塑在材料和概念上大幅扩展。布朗库西追求简化的本质形式。考尔德引入了会动的动态雕塑。装置艺术将整个空间转化为雕塑体验。当代雕塑越来越多地融合现成品、数字制造和互动元素。",
  330, [["What did Greek sculpture achieve?","Strict religious conventions","Unprecedented naturalism capturing the human form in idealized perfection","Only abstract forms","Only monumental architecture","B","文章指出希腊雕塑实现了前所未有的自然主义，以理想化的完美捕捉人体形式。"],["What does Michelangelo's David exemplify?","The rejection of human beauty","The Renaissance belief in the inherent beauty of the human form","Only religious themes","Only abstract expression","B","文章指出米开朗基罗的大卫像体现了该时期对人体形式内在美的信念。"],["Who introduced kinetic sculpture?","Michelangelo","Brancusi","Alexander Calder","Rodin","C","文章指出考尔德引入了会动的动态雕塑。"],["What did Rodin emphasize in his sculpture?","Strict academic tradition","Personal expression over idealized form","Only classical proportions","Only religious subjects","B","文章指出罗丹打破学院传统，创作强调个人表达而非理想化形式的作品。"]]],
  [183, "Photography as Art", "艺术", 1, "Photography, invented in the early nineteenth century, has evolved from a technical process for recording reality into a sophisticated art form. The debate over whether photography qualifies as art has long been settled, with photographs now commanding the same respect and value as paintings and sculptures.\n\nEarly photographers faced the question of whether the camera was merely a mechanical recording device or a tool for artistic expression. Pictorialism, a movement in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, sought to establish photography as art by manipulating images to resemble paintings, using soft focus and special printing techniques. Straight photography, championed by Ansel Adams and others, argued instead that photography's artistic value lay in its unique ability to capture the real world with clarity and precision.\n\nPhotography has expanded our understanding of the world in profound ways. Photojournalism has brought distant events into public consciousness, from war photography that revealed battlefield horrors to documentary images that spurred social reform. The Farm Security Administration photographs of the American Depression and Nick Ut's image of a napalm victim in Vietnam are examples of photographs that changed public opinion and policy.\n\nThe digital revolution has transformed photography. Smartphones have made everyone a potential photographer, and social media platforms have created new ways of sharing images. Digital manipulation tools allow unprecedented alteration of photographic reality, raising questions about authenticity. Despite these changes, the essential artistic challenge of photography remains: using light, composition, and timing to reveal truths about the world and the human experience.",
  "摄影发明于十九世纪初，已从记录现实的技术过程演变为复杂的艺术形式。摄影是否属于艺术的争论早已解决，照片现在获得了与绘画和雕塑同等的尊重和价值。\n\n早期摄影师面临相机是否仅是机械记录设备还是艺术表达工具的问题。画意主义运动试图通过操控图像使其类似绘画来确立摄影的艺术地位。直接摄影则认为摄影的艺术价值在于其以清晰精确捕捉真实世界的独特能力。\n\n摄影以深刻的方式扩展了我们对世界的理解。新闻摄影将遥远的事件带入公众意识。美国大萧条时期的农业安全局照片和越南战争中凝固汽油弹受害者的图像是改变公众舆论和政策的照片实例。\n\n数字革命改变了摄影。智能手机使每个人都成为潜在的摄影师。数字操控工具允许对摄影现实的前所未有的改变，引发关于真实性的问题。尽管发生了这些变化，摄影的基本艺术挑战仍然存在：利用光线、构图和时机揭示关于世界和人类经验的真相。",
  334, [["What did Pictorialism seek to do?","Capture reality with maximum clarity","Establish photography as art by manipulating images to resemble paintings","Only take portraits","Only photograph landscapes","B","文章指出画意主义运动试图通过操控图像使其类似绘画来确立摄影的艺术地位。"],["What did straight photography argue?","That photos should always look like paintings","That photography's artistic value lay in capturing the real world with clarity and precision","That photos should be heavily edited","That only black and white photos were art","B","文章指出直接摄影认为摄影的艺术价值在于以清晰精确捕捉真实世界。"],["What has the digital revolution done to photography?","Made it less accessible","Made everyone a potential photographer with smartphones","Eliminated professional photography","Only improved film quality","B","文章指出智能手机使每个人都成为潜在的摄影师。"],["What remains the essential artistic challenge of photography?","Using the most expensive equipment","Using light, composition, and timing to reveal truths about the world","Only taking photos of famous people","Only using film cameras","B","文章指出摄影的基本艺术挑战是利用光线、构图和时机揭示关于世界的真相。"]]],
  [184, "Theater and Drama", "艺术", 1, "Theater, one of the oldest art forms, combines storytelling, performance, and visual design to create live experiences that engage audiences emotionally and intellectually. From ancient Greek tragedies to contemporary experimental performances, theater has served as a mirror reflecting society's deepest concerns and highest aspirations.\n\nAncient Greek theater laid the foundations of Western drama. The tragedies of Aeschylus, Sophocles, and Euripides explored themes of fate, justice, and human suffering. Greek comedy, led by Aristophanes, used humor and satire to comment on politics and society. The architectural design of the Greek amphitheater, with its excellent acoustics and sightlines, established principles still followed in theater design.\n\nShakespeare transformed English drama in the late sixteenth and early seventeenth centuries, creating plays that combined poetic language, complex characters, and universal themes. His works, from the tragedy of Hamlet to the comedy of A Midsummer Night's Dream, continue to be performed worldwide more than four hundred years after they were written, testament to their enduring insight into human nature.\n\nModern theater has expanded in multiple directions. Realism, pioneered by Ibsen and Chekhov, brought everyday life to the stage. Bertolt Brecht's epic theater used alienation effects to encourage critical thinking rather than emotional immersion. Absurdist playwrights including Beckett and Ionesco questioned the meaning of existence itself. Today's theater embraces diverse voices, addresses contemporary issues, and experiments with form, from immersive performances to digital theater. The enduring appeal of theater lies in its immediacy, the unique connection between performers and audience that no other art form can replicate.",
  "戏剧是最古老的艺术形式之一，结合叙事、表演和视觉设计创造在情感和理智上吸引观众的现场体验。从古希腊悲剧到当代实验表演，戏剧一直是反映社会最深关切和最高抱负的镜子。\n\n古希腊戏剧奠定了西方戏剧的基础。埃斯库罗斯、索福克勒斯和欧里庇得斯的悲剧探索命运、正义和人类苦难的主题。希腊喜剧以幽默和讽刺评论政治和社会。\n\n莎士比亚在十六世纪末和十七世纪初改变了英国戏剧，创作了结合诗意语言、复杂角色和普遍主题的戏剧。他的作品在写成四百多年后仍在世界各地演出。\n\n现代戏剧向多个方向扩展。由易卜生和契诃夫开创的现实主义将日常生活搬上舞台。布莱希特的史诗剧使用间离效果鼓励批判性思考。荒诞派剧作家包括贝克特和尤内斯库质疑存在本身的意义。戏剧的持久吸引力在于其即时性，表演者与观众之间独特的联系。",
  332, [["What themes did Greek tragedies explore?","Only romantic love","Fate, justice, and human suffering","Only comedic situations","Only historical events","B","文章指出希腊悲剧探索命运、正义和人类苦难的主题。"],["What did Bertolt Brecht's epic theater use?","Emotional immersion techniques","Alienation effects to encourage critical thinking","Only musical numbers","Only traditional costumes","B","文章指出布莱希特的史诗剧使用间离效果鼓励批判性思考而非情感沉浸。"],["What makes theater unique compared to other art forms?","It is always recorded","The immediate connection between performers and audience","It is always performed outdoors","It never uses words","B","文章指出戏剧的持久吸引力在于其即时性，表演者与观众之间独特的联系。"],["Who are the absurdist playwrights mentioned?","Shakespeare and Ibsen","Beckett and Ionesco","Aeschylus and Sophocles","Brecht and Chekhov","B","文章指出荒诞派剧作家包括贝克特和尤内斯库。"]]],
  [185, "Literature and the Human Condition", "艺术", 2, "Literature, through the written word, explores the depths of human experience, offering insights into emotions, relationships, and societies that no other medium can provide. From ancient epics to contemporary novels, literature has served as both entertainment and a vehicle for understanding ourselves and our world.\n\nThe earliest literary works addressed fundamental questions of existence. The Epic of Gilgamesh, dating from around 2100 BCE, grapples with mortality and the search for meaning. Homer's Iliad and Odyssey explore heroism, honor, and the human cost of war. These ancient texts demonstrate that the concerns of literature, love, loss, justice, and identity, are timeless.\n\nThe novel emerged as a dominant literary form in the eighteenth century and has since become the primary vehicle for literary exploration. Works by Dickens, Tolstoy, and Austen created vivid social panoramas that illuminated the conditions of their times. The novel's capacity for interiority, its ability to represent characters' inner lives, gives readers access to experiences and perspectives vastly different from their own.\n\nLiterature serves crucial social functions. It builds empathy by allowing readers to inhabit other minds and experiences. It preserves cultural memory and transmits values across generations. It challenges power by giving voice to the marginalized and critiquing injustice. In a world of rapid change and information overload, literature offers a space for slow, deep engagement with complex ideas and emotions, a quality that becomes more valuable as other media grow faster and more fragmented.",
  "文学通过文字探索人类经验的深度，提供关于情感、关系和社会的洞察。从古代史诗到当代小说，文学既服务于娱乐，也是理解我们自身和世界的载体。\n\n最早的文学作品探讨了存在的基本问题。《吉尔伽美什史诗》探索死亡和寻找意义。荷马的《伊利亚特》和《奥德赛》探索英雄主义、荣誉和战争的人代价。\n\n小说在十八世纪出现为主要的文学形式，此后成为文学探索的主要载体。狄更斯、托尔斯泰和奥斯汀的作品创造了生动的社会全景。小说表现内心生活的能力使读者能够接触与自己截然不同的经验和观点。\n\n文学承担关键的社会功能。它通过让读者设身处地体验他人的心灵和经验来建立共情。它保存文化记忆，挑战权力。在一个快速变化和信息过载的世界中，文学提供了缓慢深入参与复杂思想和情感的空间。",
  326, [["What does the Epic of Gilgamesh grapple with?","Modern technology","Mortality and the search for meaning","Romantic comedy","Space exploration","B","文章指出《吉尔伽美什史诗》探索死亡和寻找意义。"],["When did the novel emerge as a dominant literary form?","In ancient Greece","In the eighteenth century","In the twentieth century","In the Middle Ages","B","文章指出小说在十八世纪出现为主要的文学形式。"],["How does literature build empathy?","By only presenting facts","By allowing readers to inhabit other minds and experiences","By telling readers what to think","By avoiding emotional content","B","文章指出文学通过让读者设身处地体验他人的心灵和经验来建立共情。"],["What quality of literature becomes more valuable as other media grow faster?","Its brevity","Its capacity for slow, deep engagement with complex ideas and emotions","Its use of images only","Its simplicity","B","文章指出文学提供缓慢深入参与复杂思想和情感的空间，在其他媒体变得更快更碎片化时这变得更加宝贵。"]]],
  [186, "The Art of Calligraphy", "艺术", 1, "Calligraphy, the art of beautiful handwriting, occupies a special place in artistic traditions worldwide. Particularly revered in East Asian and Islamic cultures, calligraphy transcends mere writing to become a visual art form that embodies spiritual, philosophical, and aesthetic values.\n\nChinese calligraphy, with a history spanning over three thousand years, is considered the supreme visual art form in Chinese culture. Using a brush, ink, paper, and inkstone, known as the Four Treasures of the Study, calligraphers create characters that express both meaning and emotion. The stroke order, rhythm, pressure, and speed of the brush reveal the calligrapher's character and state of mind. Masters like Wang Xizhi, whose Preface to the Poems Collected from the Orchid Pavilion is considered the greatest calligraphy work, achieved legendary status.\n\nIslamic calligraphy developed as a response to religious prohibitions against figurative art. Arabic script became the primary vehicle for artistic expression in the Islamic world, adorning mosques, manuscripts, and everyday objects. The beauty of the written word, particularly the Quran, was believed to reflect divine beauty. Scripts including Naskh, Thuluth, and Kufic each have distinct characteristics suited to different purposes.\n\nWestern calligraphy, from medieval illuminated manuscripts to modern lettering arts, has its own rich traditions. The Book of Kells and other medieval manuscripts combined calligraphy with elaborate decoration to create books of extraordinary beauty. Today, calligraphy experiences a revival as artists and designers rediscover the beauty and meaning of hand-lettered text in an age of digital uniformity.",
  "书法是优美书写的艺术，在世界艺术传统中占有特殊地位。在东亚和伊斯兰文化中尤其受尊崇，书法超越了单纯的书写，成为体现精神、哲学和审美价值的视觉艺术形式。\n\n中国书法有超过三千年的历史，被认为是中国文化中最高的视觉艺术形式。使用笔、墨、纸、砚即文房四宝，书法家创造既表达意义又表达情感的文字。笔画的顺序、节奏、压力和速度揭示了书法家的品格和心境。\n\n伊斯兰书法作为对宗教禁止具象艺术的回应而发展。阿拉伯文字成为伊斯兰世界艺术表达的主要载体。文字之美，特别是古兰经之美，被认为反映了神圣之美。\n\n西方书法从中世纪装饰手稿到现代字体艺术，有其丰富的传统。今天，在数字统一的时代，书法正在复兴，艺术家和设计师重新发现手写文字的美丽和意义。",
  330, [["What are the Four Treasures of the Study in Chinese calligraphy?","Brush, ink, paper, and inkstone","Gold, silver, jade, and silk","Pen, pencil, eraser, and ruler","Stone, wood, metal, and glass","A","文章指出笔、墨、纸、砚即文房四宝。"],["Why did Islamic calligraphy develop?","Because Arabic was the easiest language","As a response to religious prohibitions against figurative art","Because paper was not available","Only for commercial purposes","B","文章指出伊斯兰书法作为对宗教禁止具象艺术的回应而发展。"],["Who is considered the greatest Chinese calligrapher?","Li Bai","Wang Xizhi","Confucius","Laozi","B","文章指出王羲之的《兰亭集序》被认为是最伟大的书法作品。"],["What is causing a revival of calligraphy today?","The decline of digital technology","Artists rediscovering hand-lettered text in an age of digital uniformity","Government mandates","Only academic requirements","B","文章指出在数字统一的时代，艺术家和设计师重新发现手写文字的美丽和意义。"]]],
  [187, "Street Art and Urban Expression", "艺术", 2, "Street art, once dismissed as vandalism, has emerged as a significant contemporary art movement that transforms public spaces and challenges conventional notions of where art belongs and who it serves. From graffiti tags to elaborate murals, street art brings art out of galleries and into everyday life.\n\nThe origins of modern street art lie in the graffiti culture of 1970s New York, where young people in marginalized communities used spray paint and subway trains as their canvas. What began as territorial marking and self-expression evolved into sophisticated visual communication. Artists like Keith Haring and Jean-Michel Basquiat bridged street culture and the art establishment, bringing graffiti aesthetics into galleries.\n\nBanksy, the anonymous British artist, has become street art's most famous practitioner. His stenciled works combine humor, irony, and pointed social commentary, addressing themes including war, capitalism, and inequality. The paradox of Banksy's work, created for public consumption but selling for millions at auction, highlights tensions between street art's anti-establishment origins and its commercial appropriation.\n\nStreet art serves multiple functions in contemporary cities. It can revitalize neglected neighborhoods, turning blank walls into tourist attractions and community landmarks. It can give voice to marginalized perspectives excluded from mainstream media. It can memorialize events and honor individuals in ways that official monuments do not. However, street art also raises questions about property rights, public space, and the distinction between artistic expression and vandalism, debates that reflect broader tensions in contemporary society.",
  "街头艺术曾经被视为破坏行为，现在已发展为一个重要的当代艺术运动，将公共空间转化为艺术表达场所，挑战关于艺术归属和服务对象的传统观念。\n\n现代街头艺术的起源在于1970年代纽约的涂鸦文化，边缘化社区的年轻人使用喷漆和地铁列车作为画布。从领地标记和自我表达演变为复杂的视觉交流。凯斯·哈林和让-米歇尔·巴斯奎特等艺术家连接了街头文化和艺术机构。\n\n班克西，匿名的英国艺术家，已成为街头艺术最著名的实践者。他的模板作品结合了幽默、讽刺和尖锐的社会评论。班克西作品的悖论突显了街头艺术反体制起源与其商业挪用之间的紧张关系。\n\n街头艺术在当代城市中服务于多种功能。它可以使被忽视的社区重新焕发活力，给予被边缘化的观点发声机会。然而街头艺术也引发了关于产权、公共空间以及艺术表达与破坏行为区别的问题。",
  328, [["Where do the origins of modern street art lie?","In ancient Roman graffiti","In the graffiti culture of 1970s New York","In medieval European cathedrals","In Japanese calligraphy","B","文章指出现代街头艺术的起源在于1970年代纽约的涂鸦文化。"],["What themes does Banksy's work address?","Only abstract patterns","War, capitalism, and inequality","Only nature scenes","Only romantic themes","B","文章指出班克西的作品涉及战争、资本主义和不平等等主题。"],["What paradox does Banksy's work highlight?","Between painting and sculpture","Between street art's anti-establishment origins and its commercial appropriation","Between traditional and modern art","Between public and private art","B","文章指出班克西作品的悖论突显了街头艺术反体制起源与其商业挪用之间的紧张关系。"],["What can street art do for neglected neighborhoods?","Make them worse","Revitalize them by turning blank walls into tourist attractions and community landmarks","Only attract criminals","Only lower property values","B","文章指出街头艺术可以使被忽视的社区重新焕发活力，将空白墙壁变成旅游景点和社区地标。"]]],
  [188, "Opera: The Grand Art Form", "艺术", 2, "Opera, born in Italy at the end of the sixteenth century, represents one of the most ambitious and spectacular art forms, combining music, drama, visual design, and dance into a unified theatrical experience. Despite its reputation for exclusivity, opera's emotional power and artistic scope continue to captivate audiences worldwide.\n\nThe first operas were attempts to recreate ancient Greek drama, which was believed to have been sung entirely. Jacopo Peri's Dafne, performed in 1598, is considered the first opera, though little of its music survives. Claudio Monteverdi's L'Orfeo, premiered in 1607, established opera as a viable art form and is the earliest opera still regularly performed.\n\nThe nineteenth century is often considered opera's golden age. Italian composers including Rossini, Verdi, and Puccini created works of enduring popularity. Verdi's operas including La Traviata and Aida combined memorable melodies with dramatic intensity and social commentary. German composer Wagner revolutionized opera with his concept of Gesamtkunstwerk, a total work of art integrating music, poetry, and visual spectacle into a unified whole.\n\nOpera faces challenges in the contemporary world. Production costs are enormous, and aging audiences raise concerns about the art form's future. However, innovative approaches including HD broadcasts to cinemas, contemporary subject matter, and efforts to diversify casts and audiences are expanding opera's reach. The fundamental appeal of opera, the power of the human voice amplified by music and drama to express the deepest human emotions, remains undiminished.",
  "歌剧诞生于十六世纪末的意大利，代表最具雄心和壮观的艺术形式之一，将音乐、戏剧、视觉设计和舞蹈结合为统一的戏剧体验。尽管有排他性的名声，歌剧的情感力量和艺术范围继续吸引着全世界的观众。\n\n最早的歌剧是尝试重现古希腊戏剧。雅各布·佩里的《达芙妮》于1598年演出，被认为是第一部歌剧。蒙特威尔第的《奥菲欧》于1607年首演，确立了歌剧作为可行艺术形式的地位。\n\n十九世纪通常被认为是歌剧的黄金时代。意大利作曲家包括罗西尼、威尔第和普契尼创作了经久不衰的作品。威尔第的歌剧结合了令人难忘的旋律与戏剧强度和社会评论。德国作曲家瓦格纳以整体艺术的概念革新了歌剧。\n\n歌剧在当代世界面临挑战。制作成本巨大，观众老龄化引发了对该艺术形式未来的担忧。然而创新的途径正在扩大歌剧的影响范围。歌剧的基本吸引力——人声通过音乐和戏剧的放大来表达最深人类情感的力量——依然不减。",
  330, [["What is considered the first opera?","Monteverdi's L'Orfeo","Jacopo Peri's Dafne","Verdi's La Traviata","Wagner's Ring Cycle","B","文章指出雅各布·佩里的《达芙妮》被认为是第一部歌剧。"],["What is the earliest opera still regularly performed?","Peri's Dafne","Monteverdi's L'Orfeo","Rossini's The Barber of Seville","Puccini's La Boheme","B","文章指出蒙特威尔第的《奥菲欧》是最早仍定期演出的歌剧。"],["What concept did Wagner use to revolutionize opera?","Minimalism","Gesamtkunstwerk, a total work of art integrating music, poetry, and visual spectacle","Only using Italian language","Only using small orchestras","B","文章指出瓦格纳以整体艺术的概念革新了歌剧。"],["What innovative approaches are expanding opera's reach?","Only traditional performances","HD broadcasts to cinemas, contemporary subject matter, and diversification efforts","Only making opera shorter","Only performing in Italian","B","文章指出创新的途径包括高清影院转播、当代题材和多元化努力正在扩大歌剧的影响范围。"]]],
  [189, "The Art of Pottery and Ceramics", "艺术", 1, "Pottery and ceramics represent one of humanity's oldest and most enduring art forms, combining practical utility with artistic expression. From simple vessels for storing grain to exquisite porcelain worthy of emperors, ceramics tell the story of human civilization through clay and fire.\n\nThe earliest pottery dates back approximately 20,000 years, with fragments found in East Asia. The invention of the potter's wheel around 3500 BCE in Mesopotamia revolutionized ceramic production, allowing faster and more uniform creation of vessels. Ancient civilizations including the Chinese, Greeks, and Mayans each developed distinctive ceramic traditions reflecting their cultures and values.\n\nChinese porcelain, often called china, represents one of ceramics' highest achievements. Developed during the Eastern Han Dynasty around 200 CE, porcelain's combination of whiteness, translucency, and durability made it extraordinarily prized. For centuries, Europe attempted to replicate Chinese porcelain, finally succeeding in the early eighteenth century. The secrets of porcelain production influenced global trade and diplomacy as profoundly as any technology.\n\nContemporary ceramics straddle the boundary between art and craft. Studio potters create functional ware that embodies artistic vision. Ceramic sculptors use clay as a medium for conceptual expression. The Japanese aesthetic of wabi-sabi, finding beauty in imperfection and simplicity, has profoundly influenced modern ceramic art. Digital fabrication and new glaze technologies continue to expand ceramics' expressive possibilities, ensuring that this ancient art form remains vital and evolving.",
  "陶艺和陶瓷代表了人类最古老和最持久的艺术形式之一，将实用性与艺术表达相结合。从储存粮食的简单容器到值得皇帝拥有的精美瓷器，陶瓷通过泥土和火讲述了人类文明的故事。\n\n最早的陶器大约可追溯到2万年前。约公元前3500年美索不达米亚陶轮的发明革新了陶瓷生产。中国、希腊和玛雅等古代文明各自发展了独特的陶瓷传统。\n\n中国瓷器，常被称为china，代表陶瓷最高成就之一。约公元200年东汉时期发展，瓷器的白度、半透明性和耐久性组合使其极为珍贵。几个世纪以来欧洲试图复制中国瓷器，直到十八世纪初才成功。\n\n当代陶瓷跨越艺术与工艺的边界。工作室陶艺家创造体现艺术愿景的功能器皿。陶瓷雕塑家使用陶土作为概念表达的媒介。日本的侘寂美学深刻影响了现代陶瓷艺术。数字制造和新的釉料技术继续扩展陶瓷的表现可能性。",
  328, [["When was the potter's wheel invented?","About 10,000 BCE","Around 3500 BCE in Mesopotamia","Around 100 CE","Around 1800 CE","B","文章指出约公元前3500年美索不达米亚陶轮的发明革新了陶瓷生产。"],["When was Chinese porcelain developed?","Around 2000 BCE","Around 200 CE during the Eastern Han Dynasty","Around 1200 CE","Around 1800 CE","B","文章指出瓷器约公元200年东汉时期发展。"],["What is the Japanese aesthetic of wabi-sabi?","Preferring only perfect symmetry","Finding beauty in imperfection and simplicity","Only using bright colors","Only making large objects","B","文章指出侘寂美学在瑕疵和简约中寻找美。"],["When did Europe succeed in replicating Chinese porcelain?","In the fifteenth century","In the early eighteenth century","In the twentieth century","Never","B","文章指出欧洲直到十八世纪初才成功复制中国瓷器。"]]],
  [190, "Jazz: America's Musical Contribution", "艺术", 1, "Jazz, born in the African American communities of New Orleans in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, is widely considered America's greatest original contribution to the arts. Combining elements of blues, ragtime, and European harmony with African rhythmic and improvisational traditions, jazz created an entirely new musical language.\n\nJazz is characterized above all by improvisation, the spontaneous creation of melody and rhythm within a harmonic framework. Unlike classical music, where performers interpret composed works, jazz musicians create new music in real time, making each performance unique. This emphasis on individual expression within a collaborative framework reflects democratic ideals.\n\nThe history of jazz encompasses multiple stylistic revolutions. The swing era of the 1930s and 1940s made jazz America's popular music, with big bands led by Duke Ellington and Count Basie filling dance halls. Bebop, pioneered by Charlie Parker and Dizzy Gillespie in the 1940s, introduced complex harmonies and rapid tempos that prioritized artistic expression over danceability. Cool jazz, hard bop, free jazz, and fusion followed, each expanding jazz's boundaries.\n\nJazz has influenced virtually every subsequent popular music genre. Rock and roll, rhythm and blues, hip-hop, and electronic music all bear jazz's imprint. Jazz education has become formalized in universities worldwide. However, jazz faces challenges including declining audience share and the difficulty of sustaining live performance venues. Despite these challenges, jazz remains a living art form, with contemporary musicians continuing to innovate while honoring the tradition of creative improvisation that defines the genre.",
  "爵士乐诞生于十九世纪末和二十世纪初新奥尔良的非裔美国人社区，被广泛认为是美国对艺术最伟大的原创贡献。爵士乐结合了蓝调、散拍乐和欧洲和声的元素与非洲节奏和即兴传统，创造了全新的音乐语言。\n\n爵士乐最显著的特征是即兴演奏，在和声框架内自发地创造旋律和节奏。与演奏者诠释作曲作品的古典音乐不同，爵士音乐家实时创造新音乐。\n\n爵士乐的历史包含多次风格革命。1930和1940年代的摇摆乐时代使爵士乐成为美国的流行音乐。1940年代由查理·帕克和迪齐·吉莱斯皮开创的比波普引入了复杂的和声和快速的节奏。\n\n爵士乐影响了几乎所有后续的流行音乐流派。摇滚乐、节奏蓝调、嘻哈和电子音乐都带有爵士乐的印记。爵士乐教育已在世界各地的大学中正规化。尽管面临挑战，爵士乐仍然是一种活的艺术形式。",
  334, [["What is jazz characterized above all by?","Strict adherence to written scores","Improvisation, the spontaneous creation of melody and rhythm","Only using piano","Only performing classical pieces","B","文章指出爵士乐最显著的特征是即兴演奏。"],["What made jazz America's popular music in the 1930s and 1940s?","Bebop","The swing era with big bands","Free jazz","Fusion","B","文章指出1930和1940年代的摇摆乐时代使爵士乐成为美国的流行音乐。"],["Who pioneered bebop?","Duke Ellington and Count Basie","Charlie Parker and Dizzy Gillespie","Miles Davis and John Coltrane","Louis Armstrong and Ella Fitzgerald","B","文章指出比波普由查理·帕克和迪齐·吉莱斯皮开创。"],["What democratic ideal does jazz reflect?","Strict hierarchy","Individual expression within a collaborative framework","Complete conformity","Only following the leader","B","文章指出在合作框架内强调个人表达反映了民主理想。"]]],
  [191, "Digital Art and New Media", "艺术", 2, "Digital art, created using digital technology as an essential part of the creative process, has emerged as a major force in contemporary art. From digital painting and photography to virtual reality experiences and artificial intelligence-generated works, technology is expanding the boundaries of artistic expression in unprecedented ways.\n\nDigital art encompasses a broad spectrum of practices. Digital painting and illustration use software to create images that can mimic traditional media or explore effects impossible with physical materials. 3D modeling and animation create virtual objects and environments. Interactive installations respond to viewer input, blurring the boundary between artist and audience. Generative art uses algorithms and code to produce works that evolve according to programmed rules.\n\nArtificial intelligence has introduced new questions about creativity and authorship. AI systems trained on vast datasets of existing art can generate new images in seconds, raising debates about whether AI can truly create art and who owns AI-generated works. Some artists view AI as a powerful tool that expands creative possibilities, while others worry about its impact on human creativity and artistic employment.\n\nThe digital art market has grown dramatically, with NFTs briefly commanding astronomical prices before the market cooled. Museums and galleries increasingly exhibit digital work, though questions about preservation and display persist. The ephemeral nature of digital art, dependent on rapidly changing technology, poses unique challenges for collection and conservation. Despite these challenges, digital art represents a fundamental expansion of what art can be, reflecting the increasingly digital nature of human experience.",
  "数字艺术使用数字技术作为创作过程的必要部分，已成为当代艺术的重要力量。从数字绘画和摄影到虚拟现实体验和人工智能生成的作品，技术正以前所未有的方式扩展艺术表达的边界。\n\n数字艺术涵盖广泛的做法。数字绘画使用软件创造图像。3D建模和动画创建虚拟对象和环境。互动装置回应观众输入。生成艺术使用算法和代码产生根据编程规则演变的作品。\n\n人工智能引入了关于创造力和作者身份的新问题。在大量现有艺术数据集上训练的AI系统可以在几秒钟内生成新图像，引发了关于AI是否能真正创造艺术以及谁拥有AI生成作品的辩论。\n\n数字艺术市场急剧增长，NFT曾短暂获得天文数字的价格。博物馆和画廊越来越多地展出数字作品。数字艺术的短暂性，依赖于快速变化的技术，对收藏和保护提出了独特挑战。尽管存在这些挑战，数字艺术代表了艺术可以是什么的根本性扩展。",
  334, [["What is generative art?","Art that is always painted by hand","Art that uses algorithms and code to produce works evolving according to programmed rules","Art that only uses photographs","Art that is never displayed digitally","B","文章指出生成艺术使用算法和代码产生根据编程规则演变的作品。"],["What debate has AI art raised?","Whether computers are faster than humans","Whether AI can truly create art and who owns AI-generated works","Whether art should ever use technology","Whether AI is too expensive","B","文章指出AI引发了关于是否能真正创造艺术以及谁拥有AI生成作品的辩论。"],["What unique challenge does digital art pose?","It is too heavy to move","Its ephemeral nature dependent on rapidly changing technology poses challenges for collection and conservation","It uses too many colors","It is always too expensive","B","文章指出数字艺术的短暂性依赖于快速变化的技术，对收藏和保护提出独特挑战。"],["What happened with NFTs in the digital art market?","They had no impact","They briefly commanded astronomical prices before the market cooled","They replaced all traditional art","They were banned worldwide","B","文章指出NFT曾短暂获得天文数字的价格，随后市场降温。"]]],
  [192, "Folk Art and Cultural Identity", "艺术", 1, "Folk art, created by ordinary people within traditional cultural contexts, embodies the values, beliefs, and aesthetics of communities rather than formal artistic institutions. From quilts and pottery to woodcarving and embroidery, folk art represents the creative expression of everyday life.\n\nFolk art is distinguished by several characteristics. It is typically learned through informal apprenticeship within families or communities rather than formal training. It follows established traditions and conventions passed down through generations. It serves practical purposes as well as aesthetic ones, with beauty integrated into functional objects. And it reflects the cultural identity of the community that produces it, incorporating local materials, symbols, and stories.\n\nDifferent cultures have developed rich folk art traditions. Mexican folk art includes vibrant ceramics, textiles, and papier-mache sculptures that blend indigenous and Spanish influences. Indian folk art encompasses Madhubani paintings, block printing, and embroidery that vary dramatically by region. African folk art traditions include masks, textiles, and metalwork that carry deep spiritual and social significance.\n\nThe preservation of folk art faces challenges in the modern world. Industrialization and mass production undercut traditional craftspeople. Urbanization draws young people away from traditional communities. Globalization can homogenize distinctive local styles. However, folk art also demonstrates remarkable resilience. Revival movements support traditional craftspeople, fair trade organizations provide markets for folk art, and cultural tourism creates economic incentives for preservation. Folk art reminds us that creativity is not the exclusive province of trained professionals but flourishes wherever people find beauty in their daily lives.",
  "民间艺术由普通人在传统文化语境中创造，体现了社区的价值观、信仰和美学，而非正式艺术机构。从被子和陶器到木雕和刺绣，民间艺术代表了日常生活的创造性表达。\n\n民间艺术有几个区别性特征。它通常通过家庭或社区内的非正式学徒制学习而非正式训练。它遵循代代相传的既定传统和惯例。它同时服务于实用目的和审美目的。它反映了创造它的社区的文化认同。\n\n不同文化发展了丰富的民间艺术传统。墨西哥民间艺术包括融合土著和西班牙影响的鲜艳陶瓷和纺织品。印度民间艺术包括因地区而异的面绘画、木版印刷和刺绣。非洲民间艺术传统包括具有深层精神和社会意义的面具、纺织品和金属工艺。\n\n民间艺术的保存在现代世界面临挑战。工业化和大规模生产削弱了传统工匠。城市化将年轻人从传统社区吸引走。然而民间艺术也展示了非凡的韧性。复兴运动支持传统工匠，公平贸易组织为民间艺术提供市场。民间艺术提醒我们创造力不是受过训练的专业人士的专属领域。",
  336, [["How is folk art typically learned?","Through formal university training","Through informal apprenticeship within families or communities","Through online courses only","Through reading books only","B","文章指出民间艺术通常通过家庭或社区内的非正式学徒制学习。"],["What does folk art reflect?","Only global trends","The cultural identity of the community that produces it","Only individual expression","Only commercial interests","B","文章指出民间艺术反映了创造它的社区的文化认同。"],["What challenge does industrialization pose to folk art?","It has no effect","It undercuts traditional craftspeople through mass production","It only helps folk art","It creates more folk artists","B","文章指出工业化和大规模生产削弱了传统工匠。"],["What does folk art remind us about creativity?","That only professionals can be creative","That creativity flourishes wherever people find beauty in their daily lives, not just among trained professionals","That creativity is only for the wealthy","That creativity requires expensive tools","B","文章指出民间艺术提醒我们创造力在任何人们在日常生活中发现美的地方都蓬勃发展。"]]],
  [193, "Fashion as Art", "艺术", 2, "Fashion, once considered merely a commercial industry or a frivolous pursuit, is increasingly recognized as a legitimate art form that combines design, craftsmanship, cultural commentary, and personal expression. The boundary between fashion and art has become increasingly blurred in the twenty-first century.\n\nHaute couture, the creation of custom-fitted clothing using the finest materials and techniques, represents fashion at its most artistic. A single haute couture garment may require hundreds of hours of handwork by skilled artisans. Designers like Alexander McQueen transformed fashion shows into theatrical performances, using clothing as a medium for storytelling and emotional expression. The Metropolitan Museum of Art's annual fashion exhibitions attract millions of visitors, confirming fashion's place in the art world.\n\nFashion reflects and shapes cultural values. The minimalist aesthetic of the 1990s reflected a reaction against the excess of the 1980s. Streetwear's rise from skate and hip-hop culture challenged fashion's elitist hierarchies. Sustainable fashion addresses environmental concerns, using recycled materials and ethical production methods. Fashion can be subversive, as when punk style transformed safety pins and torn clothing into statements of rebellion.\n\nThe relationship between fashion and identity is profound. Clothing communicates membership in social groups, professional status, and personal values. Cultural appropriation in fashion, when designers borrow elements from marginalized cultures without acknowledgment or respect, has sparked important conversations about power, representation, and respect. The most thoughtful fashion designers engage with these issues, creating work that is not only beautiful but also socially conscious and culturally informed.",
  "时尚曾被认为是纯粹的商业产业或轻浮的追求，现在越来越被认为是一种合理的艺术形式，结合了设计、工艺、文化评论和个人表达。时尚与艺术之间的界限在二十一世纪变得越来越模糊。\n\n高级定制时装使用最好的材料和技术创造量身定制的服装，代表时尚最具艺术性的一面。一件高级定制服装可能需要熟练工匠数百小时的手工。亚历山大·麦昆等设计师将时装秀转化为戏剧表演。大都会艺术博物馆的年度时装展览吸引数百万游客。\n\n时尚反映和塑造文化价值观。1990年代的极简美学反映了对1980年代过度风格的反应。街头服饰从滑板和嘻哈文化中兴起挑战了时尚的精英阶层。可持续时尚解决环境问题。\n\n时尚与身份的关系深远。服装传达社会群体成员身份、职业地位和个人价值观。时尚中的文化挪用引发了关于权力、代表性和尊重的重要对话。最有思想的设计师参与这些问题，创造不仅美丽而且具有社会意识的作品。",
  334, [["What does haute couture represent?","Mass-produced clothing","Fashion at its most artistic, using the finest materials and techniques","Only children's clothing","Only sportswear","B","文章指出高级定制时装代表时尚最具艺术性的一面。"],["How did Alexander McQueen transform fashion shows?","He made them shorter","He transformed them into theatrical performances using clothing as a medium for storytelling","He eliminated all music","He only showed black clothing","B","文章指出麦昆将时装秀转化为戏剧表演，以服装为媒介进行叙事和情感表达。"],["What does sustainable fashion address?","Only style trends","Environmental concerns using recycled materials and ethical production","Only making clothes cheaper","Only using synthetic materials","B","文章指出可持续时尚解决环境问题，使用回收材料和道德生产方法。"],["What has cultural appropriation in fashion sparked?","No discussions","Important conversations about power, representation, and respect","Only fashion trends","Only legal cases","B","文章指出时尚中的文化挪用引发了关于权力、代表性和尊重的重要对话。"]]],
  [194, "The Art of Poetry", "艺术", 1, "Poetry is perhaps the most condensed and powerful form of literary art, using language with maximum precision and impact to evoke emotions, paint images, and communicate ideas. Through rhythm, metaphor, and the careful arrangement of words, poetry achieves effects that prose cannot.\n\nPoetry's roots extend to the earliest human societies. Before writing existed, poetry served as a mnemonic device, its rhythms and rhymes making long texts memorable. Homer's epics, composed orally and transmitted by generations of bards, represent the culmination of this oral tradition. The development of writing allowed poetry to become more complex and personal, leading to the lyric poetry of Sappho and the philosophical verse of Lucretius.\n\nDifferent poetic traditions emphasize different elements. Classical Chinese poetry values concision, imagery, and the relationship between nature and human emotion. Japanese haiku distills experience into seventeen syllables, capturing a single moment with crystalline precision. Persian poetry, exemplified by Rumi and Hafez, weaves mystical and romantic themes into intricate patterns. English poetry, from Shakespeare's sonnets to modern free verse, has continually reinvented its forms.\n\nContemporary poetry embraces unprecedented diversity. Spoken word and slam poetry bring performance and social activism to the art form. Digital poetry experiments with multimedia and interactivity. Poets from previously marginalized communities are gaining recognition, expanding poetry's range of voices and perspectives. In an age of information overload, poetry's ability to compress meaning and create moments of focused attention may be more valuable than ever.",
  "诗歌也许是最浓缩和最有力的文学艺术形式，以最大的精确度和冲击力使用语言来唤起情感、描绘图像和传达思想。通过节奏、隐喻和文字的精心安排，诗歌达到了散文无法达到的效果。\n\n诗歌的根源延伸到最早的人类社会。在书写存在之前，诗歌作为记忆手段。荷马史诗代表这一口头传统的巅峰。书写的发展使诗歌变得更加复杂和个人化。\n\n不同的诗歌传统强调不同的元素。中国古典诗歌重视简洁、意象和自然与人类情感的关系。日本俳句将体验浓缩为十七个音节。波斯诗歌将神秘和浪漫主题编织成复杂的模式。\n\n当代诗歌拥抱前所未有的多样性。口语诗和诗歌竞赛将表演和社会行动主义带入艺术形式。来自以前被边缘化社区的诗人正在获得认可。在信息过载的时代，诗歌压缩意义和创造专注注意时刻的能力可能比以往任何时候都更有价值。",
  328, [["Why did poetry serve as a mnemonic device before writing?","Because people had poor vision","Because its rhythms and rhymes made long texts memorable","Because it was the law","Because only poets could read","B","文章指出诗歌的节奏和韵律使长文本变得可记忆。"],["How many syllables does a haiku contain?","Seven","Fourteen","Seventeen","Twenty-one","C","文章指出日本俳句将体验浓缩为十七个音节。"],["What do spoken word and slam poetry bring to poetry?","Only traditional forms","Performance and social activism","Only written publication","Only academic recognition","B","文章指出口语诗和诗歌竞赛将表演和社会行动主义带入艺术形式。"],["Why may poetry be more valuable than ever in the age of information overload?","Because it is the longest art form","Because of its ability to compress meaning and create moments of focused attention","Because it uses the most complex vocabulary","Because it is always free","B","文章指出在信息过载的时代，诗歌压缩意义和创造专注注意时刻的能力可能比以往任何时候都更有价值。"]]],
  [195, "Museum Studies and Cultural Preservation", "艺术", 2, "Museums serve as custodians of human cultural heritage, preserving, interpreting, and providing access to objects of artistic, scientific, and historical significance. The role of museums has evolved dramatically, from private collections of the wealthy to public institutions serving diverse audiences.\n\nThe modern museum concept emerged during the Enlightenment. The British Museum, founded in 1753, was among the first national museums open to the public, based on the principle that knowledge should be accessible to all. The Louvre transformed from a royal palace to a public museum during the French Revolution, symbolizing the democratization of art and culture.\n\nContemporary museums face complex challenges and opportunities. The question of repatriation, returning cultural artifacts to their countries of origin, has become increasingly prominent. The Elgin Marbles, the Rosetta Stone, and the Benin Bronzes are among the many objects whose ownership is contested. Museums must balance their role as global cultural custodians with the rights of source communities.\n\nDigital technology is transforming museums. Virtual tours, high-resolution imaging, and online collections make museum holdings accessible to people worldwide. Interactive exhibits use augmented reality and multimedia to create engaging experiences. Social media helps museums reach younger audiences. However, digital access cannot fully replace the experience of encountering original objects, a challenge museums navigate as they balance physical and digital engagement. The future of museums lies in becoming more inclusive, accessible, and responsive to the communities they serve.",
  "博物馆是人类文化遗产的守护者，保存、解释和提供具有艺术、科学和历史意义的物品的访问。博物馆的角色已经发生了巨大演变，从富人的私人收藏到服务于多元化观众的公共机构。\n\n现代博物馆的概念在启蒙运动期间出现。大英博物馆于1753年成立，是最早向公众开放的国家博物馆之一。卢浮宫在法国大革命期间从皇家宫殿转变为公共博物馆。\n\n当代博物馆面临复杂的挑战和机遇。归还是否将文化文物归还给原属国的问题变得越来越突出。帕台农神庙大理石雕、罗塞塔石碑和贝宁青铜器是许多所有权存在争议的物品。\n\n数字技术正在改变博物馆。虚拟参观、高分辨率成像和在线收藏使博物馆藏品向全世界的人开放。然而数字访问不能完全替代接触原物的体验。博物馆的未来在于变得更加包容、可及和响应其所服务的社区。",
  328, [["When was the British Museum founded?","In 1453","In 1753","In 1853","In 1953","B","文章指出大英博物馆于1753年成立。"],["What principle was the British Museum based on?","That only scholars should access art","That knowledge should be accessible to all","That museums should only display British art","That entry should always be expensive","B","文章指出大英博物馆基于知识应该对所有人开放的原则。"],["What is the question of repatriation about?","Returning museum items to storage","Returning cultural artifacts to their countries of origin","Moving museums to new buildings","Selling artifacts to private collectors","B","文章指出归还是否将文化文物归还给原属国的问题变得越来越突出。"],["What can digital access NOT fully replace?","Online shopping","The experience of encountering original objects","Reading books","Watching television","B","文章指出数字访问不能完全替代接触原物的体验。"]]],
  [196, "Textile Art and Weaving", "艺术", 1, "Textile art, encompassing weaving, embroidery, quilting, and tapestry, represents one of humanity's most ancient and universal creative traditions. From functional fabrics to purely decorative works, textiles have served as both practical necessities and vehicles for artistic expression throughout history.\n\nWeaving dates back to at least 5000 BCE, with evidence of early looms found in multiple ancient civilizations. The development of the horizontal loom in the medieval period enabled the creation of large-scale tapestries that adorned castle walls and told stories through thread. The Bayeux Tapestry, depicting the Norman conquest of England in 1066, is perhaps the most famous historical textile, serving as both artwork and documentary record.\n\nDifferent cultures developed distinctive textile traditions. Persian carpets are renowned for their intricate patterns and superb craftsmanship. Andean textile traditions produce vibrant fabrics with complex symbolic patterns that encode social and spiritual information. West African kente cloth uses specific colors and patterns to convey messages about status and identity. Japanese textile arts including shibori dyeing and sashiko embroidery combine beauty with practical repair.\n\nContemporary textile artists are redefining the boundaries of the medium. Artists like Sheila Hicks create monumental fiber installations that transform gallery spaces. The feminist art movement reclaimed textile arts as legitimate artistic media, challenging their dismissal as merely women's work. Sustainability concerns have renewed interest in natural dyes, organic fibers, and traditional techniques. Textile art demonstrates that the materials of daily life can be elevated to the highest artistic expression.",
  "纺织艺术涵盖编织、刺绣、拼布和挂毯，代表了人类最古老和最普遍的创意传统之一。从功能性织物到纯装饰性作品，纺织品在历史上既是实用必需品又是艺术表达的载体。\n\n编织至少可追溯到公元前5000年。中世纪水平织机的发展使创造大规模挂毯成为可能。贝叶挂毯描绘了1066年诺曼征服英格兰，也许是最著名的历史纺织品。\n\n不同文化发展了独特的纺织传统。波斯地毯以复杂的图案和精湛的工艺著称。安第斯纺织传统产生编码社会和精神信息的鲜艳织物。西非肯特布使用特定的颜色和图案传达关于地位和身份的信息。\n\n当代纺织艺术家正在重新定义媒介的边界。女性主义艺术运动将纺织艺术重新认定为合法的艺术媒介，挑战了它们被轻视为仅是妇女工作的观念。可持续性关注重新激发了对天然染料、有机纤维和传统技术的兴趣。纺织艺术证明日常生活的材料可以被提升到最高的艺术表达。",
  334, [["How far back does weaving date?","To at least 5000 BCE","To at least 1000 CE","To the eighteenth century","To the twentieth century","A","文章指出编织至少可追溯到公元前5000年。"],["What does the Bayeux Tapestry depict?","The French Revolution","The Norman conquest of England in 1066","Ancient Greek mythology","Chinese history","B","文章指出贝叶挂毯描绘了1066年诺曼征服英格兰。"],["What do West African kente cloth patterns convey?","Only decorative purposes","Messages about status and identity","Only religious themes","Only weather patterns","B","文章指出西非肯特布使用特定的颜色和图案传达关于地位和身份的信息。"],["What did the feminist art movement do for textile arts?","Rejected them completely","Reclaimed them as legitimate artistic media, challenging their dismissal as women's work","Made them illegal","Only used them for fashion","B","文章指出女性主义艺术运动将纺织艺术重新认定为合法的艺术媒介。"]]],
  [197, "Animation as an Art Form", "艺术", 1, "Animation, the art of creating the illusion of movement through a sequence of images, has evolved from simple optical toys to one of the most technologically sophisticated and artistically versatile forms of visual expression. Today, animation encompasses everything from hand-drawn cartoons to photorealistic computer-generated imagery.\n\nThe principles of animation were established in the early twentieth century by Walt Disney Studios. The Twelve Basic Principles of Animation, including squash and stretch, timing, and anticipation, give animated characters weight, personality, and believability. These principles, developed for hand-drawn animation, remain relevant across all animation techniques.\n\nDifferent cultures have developed distinctive animation traditions. Japanese anime encompasses a wide range of genres and artistic styles, often featuring complex narratives and mature themes. Studio Ghibli, co-founded by Hayao Miyazaki, produces films celebrated worldwide for their artistic beauty and environmental themes. European animation often emphasizes artistic experimentation over commercial appeal, while American animation dominates global commercial markets.\n\nDigital technology has transformed animation production. Computer-generated animation, pioneered by Pixar with Toy Story in 1995, has become the dominant form of feature animation. Motion capture technology translates actors' movements into digital characters. Stop-motion animation, though labor-intensive, continues to produce distinctive works. The expansion of streaming platforms has created unprecedented demand for animated content. Animation's ability to create entire worlds unrestricted by physical reality makes it uniquely suited to storytelling in the digital age.",
  "动画是通过一系列图像创造运动幻觉的艺术，已从简单的光学玩具演变为技术最复杂和艺术最通用的视觉表达形式之一。\n\n动画原理由沃尔特·迪士尼工作室在二十世纪初确立。动画的十二个基本原则赋予动画角色重量、个性和可信度。这些原则在所有动画技术中仍然适用。\n\n不同文化发展了独特的动画传统。日本动画涵盖广泛的类型和艺术风格。由宫崎骏联合创立的吉卜力工作室制作的影片因艺术美感和环境主题而闻名世界。欧洲动画通常强调艺术实验而非商业吸引力。\n\n数字技术改变了动画制作。由皮克斯在1995年以《玩具总动员》开创的计算机生成动画已成为长片动画的主导形式。流媒体平台的扩展创造了对动画内容前所未有的需求。动画创造不受物理现实限制的整个世界的能力使其在数字时代的叙事中独具优势。",
  330, [["Who established the principles of animation?","Hayao Miyazaki","Walt Disney Studios","Pixar alone","Japanese animators","B","文章指出动画原理由沃尔特·迪士尼工作室在二十世纪初确立。"],["What was the first computer-generated feature animation?","Akira","The Lion King","Toy Story by Pixar in 1995","Spirited Away","C","文章指出由皮克斯在1995年以《玩具总动员》开创计算机生成长片动画。"],["What is distinctive about Japanese anime?","It only uses traditional techniques","It encompasses a wide range of genres and artistic styles, often with complex narratives","It is only for children","It never uses digital technology","B","文章指出日本动画涵盖广泛的类型和艺术风格，通常具有复杂的叙事和成熟的主题。"],["What makes animation uniquely suited to storytelling in the digital age?","Its low cost","Its ability to create entire worlds unrestricted by physical reality","Its short length","Its use of only human actors","B","文章指出动画创造不受物理现实限制的整个世界的能力使其在数字时代的叙事中独具优势。"]]],
  [198, "The Art of Mosaics", "艺术", 1, "Mosaics, images created by assembling small pieces of colored glass, stone, or other materials, represent one of the most durable and visually striking art forms in human history. From ancient Roman villas to modern public spaces, mosaics have decorated and informed for thousands of years.\n\nThe earliest mosaics date back to Mesopotamia around 3000 BCE, using colored cones embedded in walls. Greek and Roman mosaicists elevated the art form to extraordinary heights, creating intricate floor and wall decorations that depicted mythological scenes, geometric patterns, and everyday life. The Alexander Mosaic from Pompeii, showing Alexander the Great in battle, demonstrates the artistic sophistication achievable in this medium.\n\nByzantine mosaics represent perhaps the medium's greatest achievement. The mosaics of Ravenna, Italy, and Hagia Sophia in Istanbul use gold tesserae to create shimmering images of divine figures that seem to glow with otherworldly light. The spiritual purpose of Byzantine mosaics, to create a vision of heavenly glory on earth, gave the medium its most transcendent expression.\n\nContemporary mosaic artists continue to innovate. Public art projects use mosaics to enliven urban spaces. Community mosaic projects bring people together to create collaborative artworks. New materials including recycled glass, ceramic, and found objects expand the medium's palette. Digital design tools help plan complex installations. The enduring appeal of mosaics lies in their unique combination of permanence and fragmentation, creating unified images from countless individual pieces, a metaphor for how communities build meaning from diverse contributions.",
  "马赛克是通过组装小片彩色玻璃、石头或其他材料来创造图像的艺术，代表了人类历史上最耐用和视觉上最引人注目的艺术形式之一。\n\n最早的马赛克可追溯到约公元前3000年的美索不达米亚。希腊和罗马的马赛克艺术家将这一艺术形式提升到非凡的高度，创造了描绘神话场景、几何图案和日常生活的复杂地板和墙壁装饰。\n\n拜占庭马赛克也许代表了该媒介最伟大的成就。拉文纳和圣索菲亚大教堂的马赛克使用金色镶嵌片创造似乎发出超凡光芒的神圣形象。\n\n当代马赛克艺术家继续创新。公共艺术项目使用马赛克活跃城市空间。社区马赛克项目汇集人们共同创作合作艺术品。新材料包括回收玻璃、陶瓷和现成品扩展了该媒介的调色板。马赛克的持久吸引力在于其永久性和碎片化的独特组合，从无数个别碎片创造统一图像。",
  328, [["How far back do the earliest mosaics date?","To about 3000 BCE in Mesopotamia","To about 1000 CE","To the Renaissance","To the nineteenth century","A","文章指出最早的马赛克可追溯到约公元前3000年的美索不达米亚。"],["What do Byzantine mosaics use to create shimmering images?","Only white marble","Gold tesserae to create images that seem to glow with otherworldly light","Only blue paint","Only wood","B","文章指出拜占庭马赛克使用金色镶嵌片创造似乎发出超凡光芒的形象。"],["What does the Alexander Mosaic from Pompeii depict?","A Roman banquet","Alexander the Great in battle","A Greek temple","A sea creature","B","文章指出庞贝的亚历山大马赛克展示了亚历山大大帝在战斗中。"],["What metaphor do mosaics provide?","For military conquest","For how communities build meaning from diverse contributions","For economic competition","For technological progress","B","文章指出马赛克从无数个别碎片创造统一图像，是社区如何从多样贡献中构建意义的隐喻。"]]],
  [199, "Performance Art", "艺术", 2, "Performance art, in which the artist's own body and actions become the medium, challenges conventional distinctions between art and life, artist and audience, object and experience. Emerging as a distinct art form in the 1960s, performance art emphasizes the ephemerality and immediacy of live experience over the creation of lasting objects.\n\nPerformance art arose from several converging impulses. The desire to break free from the commercial art market, which commodified art objects, led artists to create work that could not be bought or sold. The influence of theater and dance pushed visual artists toward time-based, body-centered practices. Political movements including feminism and civil rights provided subject matter and urgency. Artists like Marina Abramovic, Yoko Ono, and Joseph Beuys used their bodies as sites of artistic inquiry.\n\nMarina Abramovic has become performance art's most celebrated figure. Her work often involves extreme physical and mental endurance, pushing her body to its limits. In The Artist Is Present, she sat silently across from museum visitors for over 700 hours, creating intense one-on-one encounters that moved many to tears. This work demonstrated performance art's power to create genuine human connection in an art world often criticized for its pretension.\n\nPerformance art raises fundamental questions about the nature of art. If art exists only in the moment of its performance, how is it documented, preserved, or collected? If the artist's body is the medium, what happens when the performance ends? These questions challenge traditional art historical frameworks and expand our understanding of what art can be. Performance art insists that art is not just about objects but about experiences, relationships, and the transformative potential of live encounter.",
  "表演艺术中，艺术家自己的身体和行动成为媒介，挑战了艺术与生活、艺术家与观众、物品与体验之间的传统区分。表演艺术在1960年代作为独立艺术形式出现，强调现场体验的短暂性和即时性。\n\n表演艺术源于多种汇聚的冲动。摆脱将艺术品商品化的商业艺术市场的渴望导致艺术家创作无法买卖的作品。政治运动包括女权主义和民权运动提供了主题和紧迫性。\n\n玛丽娜·阿布拉莫维奇已成为表演艺术最著名的人物。在《艺术家在场》中，她与博物馆访客对坐超过700小时，创造了一对一的强烈接触。这件作品展示了表演艺术在经常被批评为做作的艺术世界中创造真正人际联系的力量。\n\n表演艺术提出了关于艺术本质的根本问题。如果艺术只存在于表演的瞬间，如何记录、保存或收藏？这些问题挑战了传统的艺术史框架，扩展了我们对艺术可以是什么的理解。",
  332, [["When did performance art emerge as a distinct art form?","In the 1920s","In the 1940s","In the 1960s","In the 1990s","C","文章指出表演艺术在1960年代作为独立艺术形式出现。"],["Why did artists turn to performance art?","To make more money","To break free from the commercial art market that commodified art objects","To become actors in Hollywood","Only to entertain","B","文章指出摆脱将艺术品商品化的商业艺术市场的渴望导致艺术家转向表演艺术。"],["How long did Abramovic sit in The Artist Is Present?","For 7 hours","For 70 hours","For over 700 hours","For 7,000 hours","C","文章指出阿布拉莫维奇在《艺术家在场》中与访客对坐超过700小时。"],["What fundamental question does performance art raise?","Whether art should be free","If art exists only in the moment of performance, how is it documented, preserved, or collected?","Whether performance art is real art","Whether artists should be paid","B","文章指出如果艺术只存在于表演的瞬间，如何记录、保存或收藏这一根本问题。"]]],
  [200, "Public Art and Community", "艺术", 1, "Public art, created for and displayed in public spaces, transforms shared environments into sites of beauty, contemplation, and community dialogue. From monumental sculptures in city squares to murals on building walls, public art makes artistic experience accessible to everyone, not just those who visit galleries and museums.\n\nThe history of public art stretches back millennia, from ancient Egyptian obelisks and Roman triumphal arches to medieval cathedral sculptures. These works served to commemorate events, project power, and express communal values. In the twentieth century, thePercent for Art programs, which allocate a percentage of public construction budgets to art, institutionalized public art creation in many countries.\n\nPublic art serves multiple functions in contemporary society. It can enhance the aesthetic quality of public spaces, transforming sterile environments into engaging ones. It can commemorate historical events and honor community members. It can stimulate economic development by making areas more attractive to residents and visitors. It can foster community identity and pride.\n\nHowever, public art also generates controversy. Questions about what constitutes good public art, who decides what is displayed in public spaces, and whether public funds should support controversial works spark heated debates. The destruction or removal of public monuments, particularly those associated with colonialism or slavery, has become a significant cultural and political issue. The best public art engages these tensions, creating works that invite participation and dialogue rather than imposing a single viewpoint, reflecting the diversity and dynamism of the communities it serves.",
  "公共艺术是为公共空间创作并在其中展示的艺术，将共享环境转化为美、沉思和社区对话的场所。从城市广场的纪念性雕塑到建筑墙壁上的壁画，公共艺术使每个人都能获得艺术体验。\n\n公共艺术的历史可以追溯到数千年前。这些作品服务于纪念事件、展示权力和表达社区价值观。在二十世纪，许多国家通过将公共建设预算的一定比例分配给艺术的计划来制度化公共艺术创作。\n\n公共艺术在当代社会中服务于多种功能。它可以提升公共空间的美学质量，纪念历史事件，刺激经济发展，培养社区认同和自豪感。\n\n然而公共艺术也引发争议。关于什么构成好的公共艺术、谁决定在公共空间展示什么以及公共资金是否应支持有争议的作品的问题引发激烈辩论。与殖民主义或奴隶制相关的公共纪念碑的破坏或移除已成为重要的文化和政治问题。最好的公共艺术参与这些张力，创造邀请参与和对话而非强加单一观点的作品。",
  330, [["What do Percent for Art programs do?","Charge artists a percentage of their income","Allocate a percentage of public construction budgets to art","Give 100% of art sales to the public","Only fund painting projects","B","文章指出许多国家通过将公共建设预算的一定比例分配给艺术的计划来制度化公共艺术创作。"],["What is one function of public art in contemporary society?","Only to fill empty space","Enhancing aesthetic quality, commemorating events, stimulating economic development, and fostering community identity","Only to advertise products","Only to hide ugly buildings","B","文章指出公共艺术提升美学质量、纪念事件、刺激经济发展和培养社区认同。"],["What significant issue has the destruction or removal of public monuments become?","Only a minor concern","A significant cultural and political issue, particularly for monuments associated with colonialism or slavery","Only an art world debate","Only a legal technicality","B","文章指出与殖民主义或奴隶制相关的公共纪念碑的破坏或移除已成为重要的文化和政治问题。"],["What does the best public art do?","Impose a single viewpoint","Invite participation and dialogue, reflecting the diversity of communities it serves","Only serve tourists","Only be visually impressive","B","文章指出最好的公共艺术创造邀请参与和对话而非强加单一观点的作品。"]]],
  [201, "Graphic Design and Visual Communication", "艺术", 1, "Graphic design is the art of visual communication, combining images, text, and ideas to convey information and create experiences. From road signs to corporate logos, from book covers to website interfaces, graphic design shapes how we navigate and understand the visual world.\n\nThe roots of graphic design lie in ancient writing systems and illuminated manuscripts, but the profession emerged in the early twentieth century with the development of modern printing and mass communication. The Bauhaus school integrated art, craft, and technology, establishing principles of functional design that remain influential. Swiss design, also known as the International Typographic Style, emphasized clarity, objectivity, and mathematical precision in layout.\n\nKey principles of effective graphic design include hierarchy, which guides the viewer's eye through information in order of importance; contrast, which creates visual interest and organizes content; alignment, which creates order and connection; and repetition, which builds consistency and recognition. Typography, the art of arranging type, is perhaps the most fundamental skill in graphic design, as most designs involve the presentation of text.\n\nDigital technology has revolutionized graphic design. Desktop publishing in the 1980s democratized design tools. The internet created new platforms and formats including web design, user interface design, and motion graphics. Artificial intelligence now assists with tasks from layout generation to font pairing. Despite technological advances, the core challenge of graphic design remains the same: using visual elements to communicate messages clearly, effectively, and beautifully.",
  "平面设计是视觉传达的艺术，结合图像、文字和想法来传达信息和创造体验。从路牌到企业标志，从书籍封面到网站界面，平面设计塑造了我们在视觉世界中导航和理解的方式。\n\n平面设计的根源在于古代书写系统和装饰手稿，但该职业在二十世纪初随着现代印刷和大众传播的发展而出现。包豪斯学校整合了艺术、工艺和技术，确立了仍然有影响力的功能设计原则。瑞士设计强调布局的清晰性、客观性和数学精确性。\n\n有效平面设计的关键原则包括层次、对比、对齐和重复。字体排印是平面设计中最基本的技能，因为大多数设计涉及文字的呈现。\n\n数字技术彻底改变了平面设计。1980年代的桌面出版使设计工具民主化。互联网创造了包括网页设计、用户界面设计和动态图形在内的新平台和格式。尽管技术进步，平面设计的核心挑战仍然相同：使用视觉元素清晰、有效和美观地传达信息。",
  334, [["What school integrated art, craft, and technology in design?","The Renaissance Academy","The Bauhaus school","The Florence School of Art","The Paris Academy","B","文章指出包豪斯学校整合了艺术、工艺和技术。"],["What does hierarchy in graphic design do?","Makes everything the same size","Guides the viewer's eye through information in order of importance","Only uses large fonts","Eliminates all text","B","文章指出层次引导观众的眼睛按重要性顺序浏览信息。"],["What is perhaps the most fundamental skill in graphic design?","Painting","Photography","Typography, the art of arranging type","Sculpture","C","文章指出字体排印也许是平面设计中最基本的技能。"],["What did desktop publishing in the 1980s do?","Made design tools more expensive","Democratized design tools","Eliminated all designers","Only worked for newspapers","B","文章指出1980年代的桌面出版使设计工具民主化。"]]],
  [202, "The Art of Garden Design", "艺术", 1, "Garden design, the art of creating beautiful and meaningful outdoor spaces, represents one of humanity's most enduring creative traditions. Gardens serve as places of beauty, contemplation, food production, and spiritual renewal, reflecting the cultures and values of their creators.\n\nDifferent civilizations have developed distinctive garden traditions. Japanese gardens seek to represent the essence of nature in miniature, using carefully placed rocks, water features, and pruned plants to evoke landscapes of profound simplicity and tranquility. The concept of shakkei, or borrowed scenery, integrates distant views into the garden's composition. Islamic gardens, with their geometric layouts and water channels, represent paradise on earth and provide cooling oases in arid climates.\n\nEuropean garden design has oscillated between formal and naturalistic approaches. The French formal garden, exemplified by Versailles, imposes geometric order on nature through carefully trimmed hedges, symmetrical layouts, and grand axes. The English landscape garden, developing in the eighteenth century, rejected this formality in favor of idealized natural landscapes with rolling lawns, lakes, and classical temples.\n\nContemporary garden design faces new imperatives. Climate change demands gardens that conserve water and support biodiversity. Urbanization creates the need for green spaces in densely populated areas. The therapeutic benefits of gardens, increasingly supported by research, inform the design of healing gardens in healthcare settings. Vertical gardens and rooftop gardens bring greenery to places where ground-level space is scarce. Garden design reminds us that the relationship between humans and nature is not merely practical but deeply aesthetic and spiritual.",
  "园林设计是创造美丽和有意义的户外空间的艺术，代表了人类最持久的创意传统之一。花园作为美、沉思、食物生产和精神更新的场所，反映了创造者的文化和价值观。\n\n不同文明发展了独特的园林传统。日本园林寻求以微缩形式表现自然的本质，使用精心放置的岩石、水景和修剪的植物。借景的概念将远处景观融入园林的构图。伊斯兰园林以其几何布局和水渠代表大地上的天堂。\n\n欧洲园林设计在正式和自然主义方法之间摆动。以凡尔赛为代表的法国正式园林通过精心修剪的树篱、对称布局和宏伟轴线将几何秩序强加于自然。十八世纪发展的英国风景园林拒绝了这种形式性，转而采用理想化的自然景观。\n\n当代园林设计面临新的迫切需求。气候变化要求节约用水和支持生物多样性的花园。城市化创造了在人口密集地区需要绿地的需求。花园的治疗效果越来越得到研究的支持。园林设计提醒我们人类与自然的关系不仅是实用的，而且是深层美学和精神上的。",
  338, [["What does the Japanese garden concept of shakkei mean?","Hidden garden","Borrowed scenery, integrating distant views into the garden's composition","Empty space","Only water features","B","文章指出借景的概念将远处景观融入园林的构图。"],["What characterizes the French formal garden?","Wild and natural landscapes","Geometric order imposed on nature through trimmed hedges, symmetrical layouts, and grand axes","Only vegetable plots","Only rock gardens","B","文章指出法国正式园林通过精心修剪的树篱、对称布局和宏伟轴线将几何秩序强加于自然。"],["What does the English landscape garden favor?","Strict geometric symmetry","Idealized natural landscapes with rolling lawns, lakes, and classical temples","Only Japanese elements","Only Islamic patterns","B","文章指出英国风景园林转而采用理想化的自然景观。"],["What new imperative does climate change create for garden design?","Gardens that use more water","Gardens that conserve water and support biodiversity","Gardens that only use tropical plants","Gardens that eliminate all plants","B","文章指出气候变化要求节约用水和支持生物多样性的花园。"]]
]];
